Q4Water escapes from the leaves by evaporation and
diffusion through the stomata. This creates a slight
shortage of water in the leaves, which causes more
water to be drawn up the xylem and into the leaves.
This in turn causes more water to be drawn up the
xylem from the roots.
Remember, the transpiration stream only goes on in the
xylem — it doesn’t involve the phloem.

7. Adaptations of Leaves and Plants
Page 214 — Fact Recall Questions
Q1It helps to prevent water loss by evaporation.
Q2So that light can pass through to the palisade layer,
which contains lots of chloroplasts for photosynthesis.
Q3E.g. the cells in the palisade mesophyll tissue contain
lots of chloroplasts. The palisade mesophyll tissue is
situated near the top of leaf, where it can get plenty of
light.
Q4They increase the rate of diffusion of gases through
the leaf.
Q5Having spines instead of leaves reduces the surface
area for water loss by evaporation. They also reduce
air flow near the surface of the plant, reducing
diffusion of water vapour from the leaf to the air.
Spines also help to stop animals eating the plant to
get water.
8. Plant Hormones
Page 217 — Fact Recall Questions
Q1The growth response of a plant to gravity.
Q2More auxin accumulates on the side of the shoot that
is in the shade than on the side in the light. Auxin
promotes cell elongation in shoots, so the cells on the
shaded side of the shoot elongate faster. This makes
the shoot bend towards the light source.
Q3More auxin accumulates on the lower side of the
root. Auxin inhibits cell elongation in roots, so the
cells on the top side of the root elongate faster. This
makes the root bend downwards towards gravity.
